'''Kilian Plunkett''' is an artist who has worked on numerous ''[[Star Wars]]'' projects. He has worked for [[Dark Horse Comics]] on several high-profile ''Star Wars'' comic series and is now at [[Lucasfilm Animation]]. He was the lead character designer on [[Cartoon Network]]'s ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'' and art director on Disney XD's ''[[Star Wars Rebels]]''.

Plunkett eventually became a fan-favorite ''Star Wars'' cover artist at Dark Horse throughout the 1990s, rising amongst the ranks of such noteworthy ''Star Wars'' comics cover painters as [[Dave Dorman]], [[Hugh Fleming]], and [[Duncan Fegredo]]. He produced a number of memorable covers and interior art for various ''Star Wars'' series and has, in one form or another, become a pivotal ''Star Wars'' artist of recent times.

In the comics world, Plunkett is known for unique covers that blend animation-style fluidity with painterly effects, dynamic action and, at times, humor.

==Biography==
Born and raised just outside of Dublin, Ireland, and was a fan of the British magazine [[Wikipedia:2000 AD|2000 AD]] where [[John Wagner]] and [[Cam Kennedy]] contributed. On his seventh birthday he watched [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'']] which had an impact on him, and would later exercise his talent drawing [[Darth Vader]] and spaceships. Around twelve years old he went through a "sad, dwarf-induced" phase of Tolkienian and sword-and-sorcery fantasy art.<ref name="shadowart">''[[The Secrets of Star Wars: Shadows of the Empire]]''</ref>

In [[1992]], twenty-one years old Plunkett submitted artwork to [[Dark Horse Comics]], including a six-page story, both hand-colored and uncolored; it involved a couple in formal dress and suit in a mansion, and a running man, who turns out to be a droid, and his head explodes; he also sent samples of characters such as [[Wikipedia:Lobo (DC Comics)|Lobo]] and [[Wikipedia:Predator (fictional species)|The Predator]]. The artwork caught the attention of [[Ryder Windham]], who was looking for an artist on [[Wikipedia:Aliens (Dark Horse Comics line)|''Alien'']], another of the company's popular movie franchises that required technical equipment and regular humans. Windham considered them the best amateur art samples he had seen. As Plunkett had not left his call number, Windham had to call his uncle in Dublin.<ref name="shadowart" />

===The 1990s===
In the '90s Plunkett moved to Portland, Oregon, working from his home studio.<ref name="shadowart" /> Plunkett's first foray into the ''Star Wars'' universe came when Windham, his former ''Alien'' editor, assigned him to do painted covers for the company's series [[Star Wars: Droids (Dark Horse)|''Star Wars: Droids'']], from issues 2 to 6 in 1994. This was the first of the company's series to focus on [[R2-D2/Legends|Artoo-Detoo]] and [[C-3PO/Legends|See-Threepio]]. Plunkett became the regular cover artist on almost all of Dark Horse's subsequent ''Droids'' comics, 16 in total. This included covers for all eight issues of the second new ''Star Wars: Droids'' series, and the [[Star Wars: Droids Special 1|''Star Wars: Droids Special'' 1]] (which reprinted a three-part ''Droids'' story from the pages of the Dark Horse Comics anthology series), both in 1995. The only ''Droids'' issues Plunkett did not paint covers for were issue 1 of the first miniseries, which was a special gatefold metallic foil cover drawn by ''[[Star Wars: Dark Empire]]'' artist [[Cam Kennedy]], and a special one-shot ''Droids'' story, [[Star Wars Droids: The Protocol Offensive|''The Protocol Offensive'']] which was entirely painted&mdash;covers and interiors&mdash;by artist [[Igor Kordey]] and co-written by See-Threepio himself, [[Anthony Daniels]]. Also in 1995, Plunkett worked as cover artist for the last two issues, issues 8 and 9, of ''[[Classic Star Wars: The Early Adventures]]'', which had been reprinting the early [[Russ Manning]] ''Star Wars'' newspaper comic strips.

[[1996]] saw Plunkett receive his first major ''Star Wars'' assignment when he provided the interior artwork for the [[Star Wars: Shadows of the Empire (comic series)|''Star Wars: Shadows of the Empire'']] six-issue comic miniseries. ''[[Shadows of the Empire]]'' was a major ''Star Wars'' event as it was the first multi-faceted, multimedia [[Lucasfilm]] release, concurrently released alongside a [[Star Wars: Shadows of the Empire (video game)|video game]] and [[Star Wars: Shadows of the Empire (novel)|novel]]. Plunkett also provided character and vehicle concept art for the project's preliminary stage, in January [[1995]], including four pages with proposals for the project's main villain, Prince [[Xizor/Legends|Xizor]]. Aware of ''Star Wars'' drawing inspiration from "samurai epics", he attempted to give Xizor an oriental look, consulting illustrations of Mongol warriors, even experimenting with an [[Wikipedia:Ushanka|''Ushanka''-hat]] or a cowl; he also elongated his face to make him more unhuman, careful not to imitate ''Star Trek''.<ref name="shadowart" />

The project continued to evolve even when Plunkett finished [[Shadows of the Empire 1|the first issue]]; he was instructed to make looser pencils for Xizor, so that inker [[P. Craig Russell]] would catch up with the final visual changes of the character. [[Jon Knoles]] credits Plunkett for giving a sleeker quality to Xizor's face by adding "a lot of nice lines". Still working for the [[Shadows of the Empire 2|second issue]], he had to erase his finished pencils of the ''[[Outrider/Legends|Outrider]]'' and other objects, and redraw them because their designs were revised by the project.<ref name="shadowart" />

Working for a major ''Star Wars'' project caused some over-excitement, and brainlock, to Plunkett, who initially attempted to fit all cool things he could think of in one page. While working for ''Shadows'' Plunkett said that the visuals of comic book characters work differently from the characters designed for a moving screen, whose dynamics must be captured on a two-dimensional static medium. A live-action character like [[Darth Vader]] — with clunky designs and details, a strangely shaped helmet and reflective surfaces that can show different each time — was more difficult to render than Superman or Batman, specifically designed for that medium.<ref name="shadowart" />

Plunkett was present at the July [[1995]] [[Wikipedia:San Diego Comic-Con|San Diego Comic-Con]], where he finally met for first time [[John Wagner]] in person, the writer of the ''Shadows'' comic.<ref name="shadowart" />

[[Ryder Windham]] noted Plunkett's uncanny talent for drawing complex details of mechanical objects, such as ships and droids, from memory. While other artists would consult model kits, Plunkett's talent allowed him to look at a photograph of a vehicle and draw it from a different angle. Plunkett found dangerous working with photo references from the [[original trilogy]], because, as he noted, the models and props are different in each one; for example he notes that [[R2-D2]]'s casing has Philips head screws in ''[[Episode IV]]'', which are gone in ''[[Episode VI]]'', looking more "otherworldy".<ref name="shadowart" />

In 1998, Plunkett drew the cover and interiors for the comedic one-shot [[The Jabba Tape|''Star Wars: The Jabba Tape'']], a loose sequel of ''Shadows of the Empire'' which featured the return of the swoop thugs [[Gizman|Big Gizz]] and [[Spiker]]. He also provided cover art for his second major ''Star Wars'' miniseries, the six-part ''[[Star Wars: Mara Jade – By the Emperor's Hand]]''. This was the first story to focus solely on its title character, the popular future wife of [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]], [[Mara Jade Skywalker|Mara Jade]]. The series was written by Jade's creator, ''Star Wars'' novelist [[Timothy Zahn]], and its covers mixed imagery of Jade in her time as the Emperor's Hand with existing ''Star Wars'' movie imagery, visually integrating her into the ''Star Wars'' mythos. That year, Plunkett also illustrated the cover of the trade-paperback collection of Dark Horse's comics adaptation of Zahn's ''Star Wars'' novel [[Dark Force Rising (comics)|''Dark Force Rising'']].

===The 2000s===
Starting in 2000, Plunkett made three contributions to the ''[[Star Wars Tales]]'' anthology series, starting with [[Star Wars Tales 4|issue #4]], in June 2000. Here Plunkett provided cover art and interior art for the story "[[Sand Blasted]]," which featured a return of [[Jabba Desilijic Tiure/Legends|Jabba the Hutt's]] nefarious swoop thugs, Big Gizz and Spiker (from ''Shadows'' and ''The Jabba Tape''), who encounter a Dark Trooper (a la the ''Star Wars'' video game ''Dark Forces'') in the ruins of [[Tatooine/Legends|Tatooine's]] Podracing arena (from Episode I).

Plunkett's next work for ''Star Wars Tales'' was in December 2000, when he provided an iconic Hamlet-inspired cover image for [[Star Wars Tales 6|issue #6]] depicting [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader]] holding See-Threepio's disembodied head. Plunkett also provided interior illustration for the accompanying story, written by veteran ''Star Wars'' editor and comics scribe Ryder Windham. In the story, "[[Thank the Maker]]," set on Cloud City during [[Star Wars: Episode V The Empire Strikes Back|''The Empire Strikes Back'']], Vader comes across Threepio's head, which leads to some bittersweet reflections on his former life as Anakin in the [[Prequel trilogy|prequels]]. Plunkett's last contribution to ''Star Wars Tales'' was with the cover to [[Star Wars Tales 11|issue #11]], which was devoted to stories about [[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]], in 2002.

Also in 2002, Plunkett provided covers for the two-part story [[Star Wars: Republic: The Devaronian Version|"The Devaronian Version"]] in Dark Horse's prequel-era ''Star Wars'' (later renamed ''[[Star Wars: Republic]]''), issues 40&ndash;41. The story featured a dishonest retelling of recent story arcs from the perspective of the series' in-house comedic rogue, a Devaronian bounty hunter named [[Vilmarh Grahrk]], recasting himself as the hero. The cover to issue 40 is an homage to the original poster for [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''A New Hope'']], with Grahrk in place of Luke Skywalker and other elements and characters from the issue's story taking the place of other poster elements. [[Star Wars (1998) 41|Issue 41's]] cover image features Villie as a great hunter, with a [[Wampa/Legends|wampa]] skin on his back and the heads of various ''Star Wars'' creatures (including the Wicket the Ewok, Jar Jar Binks, a Tusken Raider, and a Rancor) on his wall.

Starting in 2002, Plunkett worked on seven issues of ''[[Star Wars: Empire]]'', specifically providing covers artwork for the story "[[Star Wars: Empire: Darklighter|Darklighter]]," which focused for the first time on the story of Luke Skywalker's best friend [[Biggs Darklighter/Legends|Biggs Darklighter]]. Plunkett provided cover art for issues #8&ndash;12, and #15 during that story arc. His last work for ''Empire'' was in 2004 with the cover for issue #26 featuring the obscure Mos Eisley cantina character BoShek.

[[File:PlunkettC4print.jpg|thumb|250px|Plunkett's [[Celebration IV]] piece]]
In 2005, after having left Dark Horse, Plunkett got an interview for a design job for ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'' animated series on Cartoon Network. He got the interview through a friend of his from his days at Dark Horse, [[Henry Gilroy]], who had already become a transplant to the show as head writer. Gilroy showed Plunkett's work to director [[Dave Filoni]] and producer [[Catherine Winder]]. Filoni soon met with Plunkett, where the two discussed similar ideas on the look of ''Star Wars'', and Plunkett left copies of comics like ''The Jabba Tape''. A few weeks later, Filoni called Plunkett asking him to work on some of the characters in the show. The first two characters he was assigned were [[Mace Windu/Legends|Mace Windu]] and [[Palpatine/Legends|Palpatine]].

While Plunkett has worked on a bit of everything on the show, from environments to weapons to creatures, his main focus has been on character design. Later, Plunkett became lead character designer on the show. Plunkett said that when looking for inspiration while designing the new look of the CG animated characters, he has referred to the work of the original [[Star Wars: Clone Wars|2-D Cartoon Network series]] by [[Genndy Tartakovsky]] and [[Paul Rudish]], design work on the [[original trilogy]] by artists like [[Ralph McQuarrie]] and [[Joe Johnston]], and prequel movie design work by the team of [[Doug Chiang]], [[Erik Tiemens]] and [[Ryan Church]], all to try and absorb the look and feel of the movies and the existing ''Star Wars'' style. As a tribute to Plunkett, the [[PLNK-series power droid/Legends|PLNK-series power droid]], which made a "plunk" sound, was named for him.

Plunkett illustrated the cover of issue #2 of Dark Horse's [[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (comic series)|''Star Wars: The Clone Wars'' spin-off comic series]] in 2008.

Plunkett's first name was used to name a new character in ''The Clone Wars'', Admiral [[Shoan Kilian/Legends|Kilian]].<ref>{{InsiderCite|118|Rise of the Bounty Hunters (article)}}</ref>

